{"id":"d=origam-topic-4244//p=e5094f472c2248d09dea56499377902e","tags":{"__document_id":["origam-topic-4244"],"__file_type":["text/plain"],"__file_id":["83bfa10d0d294a2c860d35feb937d755"],"__file_part":["035dd5edc43c47f5a9f04ca1c606246d"],"__part_n":["0"],"__sect_n":["0"],"source":["origam-community"],"category":["docs"],"categoryId":["8"],"topicId":["4244"],"url":["https://community.origam.com/t/custom-work-queue-screen/4244"],"title":["Custom Work Queue Screen"]},"payload":{"url":"","schema":"20231218A","file":"content.txt","text":"# Custom Work Queue Screen\n\nCategory: docs\nURL: https://community.origam.com/t/custom-work-queue-screen/4244\n\n@washi (2025-10-28 08:44:26Z):\n By default, Origam automatically generates a UI for the work queue. However, such a generated screen may not be sufficient for all the tasks that the queue handles. For example, when manually handling incoming emails, users may want to preview attached documents. \n Release 2025.10 introduces custom work queue screens. This means it is possible to use a modelled screen to present information from the queue, as well as providing users with more information from other sources. \n Work queue screens are \u2018lazy loaded\u2019 and still use the list data structure from the work queue class. However, the custom screen can be designed based on a completely different data structure. The only requirements are that the root entity remains WorkQueueEntry and that the fields are referenced in the same way as in the list data structure. \n Usage is rather straightforward. \n \n \n Specify the custom screen under the work queue class. If you don\u2019t specify a method, the default method from the work queue class will be used ( GetById ). \n \n \n On the \u2018Work Queues\u2019 configuration screen in the application, enter the custom screen name in the \u2018Custom Screen Name\u2019 field.","vector_provider":"AI.Ollama.OllamaTextEmbeddingGenerator","vector_generator":"__","last_update":"2026-04-29T00: